1130":"1130","1160":"1160","Oxnam, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Oxnam, Roxburghshire, Scotland","Kirby Sigston, Yorkshire, England":"Kirby Sigston, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Colville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Colleville in Seine-Maritime, France, named with the Scandinavian personal name <i>Koli</i> (see   Cole   2) + Old French <i>ville</i> ‘settlement, village’. The Scottish branch of the family were descended from Philip <i>de Colville</i>, who came to Scotland as a household knight of kings Malcolm IV (1153–65) and William ‘the Lion’ (1165–1214)."],"variants":[{"name":"Cole","meanings":["English: usually from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Col(e)</i>, <i>Coll(e)</i>, <i>Coul(e)</i>, a pet form of <i>Nicol</i> (see   Nichol   and   Nicholas  ), a common personal name from the mid 13th century onward. English families with this name migrated to Scotland and to Ulster (especially Fermanagh).","English: occasionally perhaps from a different (early) Middle English personal name <i>Col</i>, of native English or Scandinavian origin. Old English <i>Cola</i> was originally a nickname from Old English <i>col</i> ‘coal’ in the sense ‘coal-black (of hair), swarthy’ and is the probable source of most of the examples in Domesday Book. In the northern and eastern counties of England settled by Vikings in the 10th and 11th centuries, alternative sources are Old Norse <i>Kolr</i> and <i>Koli</i> (either from a nickname ‘the swarthy one’ or a short form of names in <i>Kol-</i>), and Old Norse <i>Kollr</i> (from a nickname, perhaps ‘the bald one’).","English: nickname for someone with swarthy skin or black hair, from Middle English <i>col</i>, coul(e) ‘charcoal, coal’ (Old English <i>col</i>)."]},{"name":"Colvin","meanings":["Scottish and Irish (Donegal, Antrim): variant of   Colville  , probably reflecting a local pronunciation. The name was taken to Ulster in the 17th century.","Manx: if not identical with 1, perhaps from the Old Norse personal name <i>Kolbeinn</i>, with /v/ substituted for /b/.","English: from the rare Middle English personal name <i>Colwin</i>, <i>Colvin</i>, which may be a borrowing into English of a Welsh name whose modern form is <i>Collwyn</i> ‘white’, or of <i>colwyn</i> ‘doe, puppy, pet dog’, or of the placename <i>Colwyn</i> (Denbighshire, Radnorshire)."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705185,"age":6,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Colville was born in 1100, in Oxnam, Roxburghshire, Scotland, his father, Gilbert De  Colville, was 34 and his mother, Margaret Lindsay, was 21. He had at least 2 sons with Matilda de Aubigny. He died in 1159, in Kirby Sigston, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 59."},"et":{"1100–1159":"1100–1159","1100–Female":"1100–Surnud","1160–1213":"1160–1213","–Male":"Surnud","1066–1130":"1066–1130","1080–Female":"1080–Surnud","1080":"1080","1106":"1106","1159":"1159","1213":"1213","1100":"1100","1066":"1066","1130":"1130","1160":"1160","Oxnam, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Oxnam, Roxburghshire, Scotland","Kirby Sigston, Yorkshire, England":"Kirby Sigston, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1100–1159":"1100–1159","1100–Female":"1100–Kuollut","1160–1213":"1160–1213","–Male":"Kuollut","1066–1130":"1066–1130","1080–Female":"1080–Kuollut","1080":"1080","1106":"1106","1159":"1159","1213":"1213","1100":"1100","1066":"1066","1130":"1130","1160":"1160","Oxnam, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Oxnam, Roxburghshire, Scotland","Kirby Sigston, Yorkshire, England":"Kirby Sigston, Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"1100–1159":"1100–1159","1100–Female":"1100–Décédée","1160–1213":"1160–1213","–Male":"Décédé","1066–1130":"1066–1130","1080–Female":"1080–Décédée","1080":"1080","1106":"1106","1159":"1159","1213":"1213","1100":"1100","1066":"1066","1130":"1130","1160":"1160","Oxnam, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Oxnam, Roxburghshire, Écosse","Kirby Sigston, Yorkshire, England":"Kirby Sigston, Everwyck, Anglet